=== bundle extension matches codec (.tgz / .tar.zst) — 2026-04-28 ===

bl_bundle_build hardcoded the bundle filename to *.tgz regardless of
codec; the zstd path produced a `.tgz` containing zstd data, so plain
`tar xf <bundle>` failed on hosts without magic-byte detection (CentOS
6 floor, tar 1.23, no `--zstd` autodetect — that landed in tar 1.31).
The pragmatic fix is to make the extension match the codec rather than
push the burden onto every consumer to know which decompressor to call.

[Change] src/bl.d/42-observe-router.sh — derive bundle extension from
         codec (gz → .tgz, zst → .tar.zst); plain `tar xf` resolves on
         the CentOS 6 floor for both paths and tar 1.31+ autodetects
         .tar.zst on modern hosts.
[Change] src/bl.d/41-observe-collectors.sh — function-header comment
         on bl_bundle_build updated to name both extensions.
[Change] DESIGN.md §10.2 — bundle-shape diagram shows both filenames.
[Change] DESIGN.md §10.4 — compression note replaces "tar magic-byte
         detects codec on decompress" with the codec-matched extension
         contract and explicit tar-version provenance.
[Change] tests/04-observe.bats — happy-path test renamed to "auto codec"
         and accepts either extension; "codec zst" test strengthened to
         assert .tar.zst presence AND .tgz absence (regression guard).
[Change] tests/03-models.bats — auto-codec bundle assertion accepts
         either extension.
[Change] bl — regenerated from 27 parts via 'make bl'.

Verification: bash -n + shellcheck clean on touched files (no new
warnings); make -C tests test (debian12) → 404 tests, 0 failed in 141s;
make -C tests test-rocky9 → 404 tests, 0 failed in 137s. Both test
images carry zstd, so the auto path resolves to .tar.zst — the new
regression guard exercises it.

=== bl <verb> [...] --help bubble-up at any depth — 2026-04-28 ===

`bl <verb> --help` already routed to bl_help_<verb>, but `bl <verb>
<subverb> --help` (e.g. `bl observe file --help`, `bl run observe.file
--help`) fell through to the verb dispatcher and was rejected as an
unknown sub-verb or flag. Authoring per-subcommand help blocks would
add 18-20 new help functions and ongoing drift surface. Cheaper to
bubble the help intent up.

[Change] src/bl.d/90-main.sh — replace position-2-only help match with
         a scan over "${@:2}". If any argument is -h/--help/help, route
         to bl_help_<verb> regardless of depth. Setup must still be
         matched here (before the setup) bypass arm) so it does not
         route to bl_setup() and reject --help as an unknown flag.
[New]    tests/01-cli-surface.bats — "bl <verb> <subverb> --help bubbles
         up to verb-level help" iterates 9 representative depth-2/3
         invocations across observe/consult/run/defend/clean/case/flush.
[Change] bl — regenerated from 27 parts via 'make bl'.

Verification: bash -n + shellcheck clean (no new warnings on touched
files); make -C tests test (debian12) → 404 tests, 0 failed in 140s;
make -C tests test-rocky9 → 404 tests, 0 failed in 135s.

=== bl_defend_firewall: refuse private/loopback/link-local by default — 2026-04-26 (Tier-2C) ===

bl defend firewall <ip> applied a deny rule against any syntactically
valid IP regardless of whether the address was internal. The existing
_bl_defend_firewall_is_private_ip helper was wired only as a CDN-safelist
short-circuit (private IPs skipped the ASN lookup, then proceeded to
apply). End-to-end exercise reproduced the footgun: 'bl defend firewall
192.168.1.1' added the address to apf without any prompt. Operationally
unsafe — typo or curator hallucination against an internal range can
sever internal traffic.

[Fix] src/bl.d/82-defend.sh — bl_defend_firewall adds an explicit
      refusal gate after IP validation: if _bl_defend_firewall_is_private_ip
      matches and BL_DEFEND_FW_ALLOW_PRIVATE != "yes", emit defend_refused
      ledger entry (reason=private_ip) and return BL_EX_TIER_GATE_DENIED
      (68). Mirrors the BL_DEFEND_FW_ALLOW_BROAD_IP convention already
      established in _bl_defend_firewall_validate_ip (broad-mask floor).
      Refusal covers RFC1918 (10/8, 172.16-31/12, 192.168/16), loopback
      (127/8), and link-local (169.254/16). Existing CDN-safelist early-
      exit on private IPs remains in place — under the override path,
      apply still benefits from skipping ASN lookup.
[Fix] src/bl.d/30-preflight.sh — bl_help_defend firewall block notes
      the new refusal + override env var; complements the broader help-
      alignment commit landed earlier today.
[New] tests/06-defend.bats — three regression tests:
      - 'refuses RFC1918 / loopback / link-local by default': iterates
         five IPs across all five private/loopback/link-local prefixes,
         asserts exit 68 and refusal message;
      - 'accepts private IP with BL_DEFEND_FW_ALLOW_PRIVATE override':
         override path applies cleanly via stub backend (exit 0);
      - 'private-IP refusal emits defend_refused ledger entry': verifies
         no apply call landed (stub log empty) AND ledger has a single
         defend_refused entry for the IP with reason=private_ip.
[Change] bl — regenerated from 27 parts via 'make bl'.

Verification: bash -n + shellcheck clean; tests/06-defend.bats full
run green (26/26 including the 3 new regression cases #15/16/17);
04-observe + 00-smoke + 01-cli-surface cross-suite sweep green
(104/104).

