=== M16 P5 — 2026-04-26 (args translator + per-verb observe adapters) ===

Closes the curator-prescribed-step → bl-collector contract drift surfaced in
the M16 end-to-end run. Pre-P5: bl_run_dispatch_verb passed the curator's
{key,value}[] args JSON blob as $1 to the collector, which parses $1 as a
single flag — every curator-prescribed step landed in BL_EX_USAGE 64. The
manual end-to-end run on CASE-2026-0022 worked around this by invoking
`bl observe` directly. P5 closes the loop so `bl run <step-id>` against a
bridge-enriched pending entry actually executes the prescribed observe verb.

[New] src/bl.d/60-run.sh — bl_run_dispatch_verb now prefers <handler>_from_args
      adapter when defined; falls through to legacy passthrough otherwise.
      The fall-through preserves existing tests that mock collectors with
      raw JSON input (no behavioral regression).
[New] src/bl.d/60-run.sh — args-translation helpers:
      - bl_run_args_get <args-json> <key> — extract single value
      - bl_run_args_keys <args-json> — enumerate keys
      - bl_run_args_warn_unknown <args-json> <verb> <known-keys> — bl_warn
        for each curator-emitted key not in the verb's known set
      - bl_run_args_relative_to_iso <spec> — "72h"/"30m"/"2d"/"45s" → ISO-8601
        UTC timestamp; ISO inputs pass through unchanged
[New] src/bl.d/60-run.sh — per-verb adapters for every observe.* verb in
      schemas/step.json properties.verb.enum:
        bl_observe_file_from_args
        bl_observe_log_apache_from_args
        bl_observe_log_modsec_from_args
        bl_observe_log_journal_from_args
        bl_observe_cron_from_args
        bl_observe_proc_from_args
        bl_observe_htaccess_from_args
        bl_observe_fs_mtime_cluster_from_args
        bl_observe_fs_mtime_since_from_args
        bl_observe_firewall_from_args
        bl_observe_sigs_from_args
      Each adapter:
        - Translates curator semantic key names to collector flags
          (e.g., 'roots' → '--under', 'around'/'path' → '--around')
        - Fans out comma-separated multi-values across multiple collector
          calls (e.g., roots="/var/www,/home" → 2 fs_mtime_since invocations)
        - Strips leading "*." glob prefix from ext patterns
        - Drops unknown keys with bl_warn (non-fatal)
        - Returns first non-zero rc on multi-call dispatch
      defend.* and clean.* adapters are NOT in scope (those tiers carry
      preflight gates and operator prompts; deferred to a follow-up phase).
[New] tests/13-args-adapters.bats — 27 unit tests covering every helper plus
      every adapter, including:
        - dispatcher routing (adapter present vs fall-through)
        - relative-time conversion (72h → ISO)
        - comma-list fan-out (roots, htaccess)
        - ext glob-prefix stripping (*.php → php)
        - missing-required-arg returns 64
        - unknown keys logged but non-fatal
        - cron scope splitting (system+per-user → 2 calls)
        - cron from_file bypasses live-system flags
        - proc verify_argv flag toggle
      Stubs each underlying collector to capture invocation argv; the
      adapter's translation is what's tested, not the collector itself
      (those live in 04-observe.bats).

Tests: full debian12 suite 398/398 (was 371 in P4 followup; 27 new P5 tests).

Phase 5 — and PLAN-M16-collectors-bridge.md — complete. The end-to-end loop
runs cleanly: curator emits report_step → bridge syncs to memstore pending/
with custom_tool_use_id → operator runs `bl run <step-id>` → adapter
translates args → collector executes → writeback emits user.custom_tool_result
unblocking curator's next turn. The CASE-2026-0022 manual jq/curl glue from
the M16 demo run is now obsolete.

=== M16 P4 followup — 2026-04-26 (sentinel-review fixups) ===

Adversarial post-impl review of M16 P1-P4 surfaced 3 MAJOR findings (2 with
FALSE-POSITIVE-RISK pending live-API confirmation) and 5 MINOR. Engineer
validation against the actual code confirmed all three MAJORs as real bugs.
This commit folds the validated fixes plus 4 new regression tests.

[Fix] src/bl.d/33-bridge.sh — bl_bridge_post_step now uses bl_mem_patch
      (DELETE + POST, last-write-wins) instead of bl_mem_post (which returns
      71 on 409 but retains the OLD body). Curator re-emissions of the same
      step_id with corrected content now overwrite the prior body — the
      bridge's claimed "always sync to latest session-event truth" semantic
      now matches the implementation. Sentinel finding #5.
[Fix] src/bl.d/33-bridge.sh — cursor save block moved BEFORE the zero-event
      early return. Prior placement deadlocked on `{"data":[],"next_page":"X"}`
      responses (legitimate under filtered pagination, internal-event
      suppression, paginated DELETE-affected histories): cursor never
      advanced, next invocation re-pulled same window forever. Sentinel #4.
[Fix] src/bl.d/33-bridge.sh — bl_bridge_post_step adds a step_id format
      guard mirroring bl_run_step's CLI-dispatch boundary regex. Defense-
      in-depth against curator-poisoned `step_id` values (e.g.,
      `../../../etc/passwd`) reaching the memstore key segment. Sentinel #8.
[Fix] src/bl.d/33-bridge.sh — bl_bridge_session_to_memstore validates
      response is parseable JSON with `jq -e .` before downstream length
      queries silently treat parse failures as zero-event no-ops. Returns
      69 + error envelope on malformed JSON. Sentinel #9.
[Fix] src/bl.d/33-bridge.sh — return-code map docstring now states 64/65/69/70
      explicitly and notes that bl_mem_patch's 409→0 conversion means rc=71
      cannot surface here. Sentinel #2.
[Fix] src/bl.d/41-observe-collectors.sh — _parse_modsec_serial strips
      trailing `\r` on every input line. Real-world ModSec audit logs
      round-tripped through Windows tooling or certain SIEM archive formats
      use CRLF line endings; the boundary regex `^--<hex>-[A-Z]--$` did not
      match `\r$`-terminated lines, silently emitting zero records (same
      failure mode as the pre-M16-P1 section-tracking bug). Sentinel #6.
[Fix] src/bl.d/60-run.sh — writeback `2>/dev/null` defensive suppression
      removed; `jq -r '.custom_tool_use_id // empty'` does not write to
      stderr on a missing key, so the suppression was suppressing nothing.
      Sentinel #1.
[New] tests/03-bridge.bats — 4 sentinel-finding regression tests:
      zero-data-non-null-page cursor advance (#4); malformed JSON response
      returns 69 (#9); malformed step_id is skipped (#8); last-write-wins
      via bl_mem_patch verified by GET+POST call counts (#5).
[New] tests/fixtures/sessions-events-bridge-empty-with-cursor.json —
      saturated-cursor fixture for #4 regression test.
[New] tests/fixtures/sessions-events-bridge-malformed-step-id.json —
      adversarial step_id fixture for #8 regression test.
[New] tests/fixtures/sessions-events-bridge-malformed.txt — non-JSON
      response fixture for #9 regression test.

Tests: full debian12 suite 371/371 (was 367 in P4; 4 new sentinel tests).

Sentinel verdict: FIX-AND-SHIP. All 3 validated MAJORs addressed in this
commit. 1 MINOR (modsec regex too wide — accepts 1+ hex) and 2 MINOR
(em-dash usage, MEMORY.md staleness) deferred or addressed separately:
the m12-livetrace-observations memory entry was updated in
~/.claude/projects/...memory/m12-livetrace-observations.md to reflect
M16 P3+P4 closing the M12.5 session-creation gap (operator-local; not
committed).

=== M16 P4 — 2026-04-26 (writeback emits user.custom_tool_result) ===

[Fix] src/bl.d/60-run.sh — bl_run_step writeback session-event POST now reads
      .custom_tool_use_id from the pending step body. When present (bridge-
      enriched, M16 P3+), emits {type:"user.custom_tool_result", custom_
      tool_use_id:<id>, content:[{type:"text", text:<summary>}]} which is
      what the curator session is awaiting after a report_step custom-tool
      call. When absent (legacy step paths, mocked-step BATS tests pre-
      dating the bridge, manually-staged pending entries), falls back to
      user.message which is what the session expects pre-handshake. The
      rejection signature this closes: HTTP 400 'only user.tool_confirmation,
      user.custom_tool_result, or user.interrupt may be sent' against any
      session that is awaiting a custom_tool_result.
[New] tests/05-consult-run-case.bats — 2 new tests under M16 P4 group: one
      asserts user.custom_tool_result + matching id when the step carries
      custom_tool_use_id; the other asserts the legacy user.message fallback
      when the field is absent.
[New] tests/fixtures/memstore-step-with-tool-use-id.json — bridge-enriched
      step body fixture for the P4 happy-path test.

=== M16 P3 — 2026-04-26 (session-event → memstore-pending bridge; v0.6.0) ===

Closes the M12.5 session-creation gap noted in MEMORY.md. The curator emits
report_step custom-tool calls inside its session; the operator-facing run-step
contract reads from memstore bl-case/<case>/pending/. Without this bridge,
those two stores were disconnected — `bl run <step-id>` against a
curator-prescribed step returned 72 (not found) until the operator manually
posted the step body via curl/jq glue.

[New] src/bl.d/33-bridge.sh — bl_bridge_session_to_memstore <case-id> pulls
      agent.custom_tool_use(name=report_step) events from the case's session,
      enriches each step body with custom_tool_use_id (the session-event id),
      and POSTs to bl-case/<case>/pending/<step-id>.json. Idempotent: 409
      conflicts on already-posted steps are caught and converted to success
      (already_posted accounting). Cursor advance via state.json.session_
      cursors[case-id] using the API's opaque ?page= pagination — there is
      no ?after=<event-id> primitive (probed; rejected). Non-report_step
      custom-tool calls and non-custom-tool events are skipped silently.
[New] src/bl.d/33-bridge.sh — bl_bridge_flush_all_open_cases iterates every
      case in state.json.session_ids and bridges each. First non-zero rc is
      surfaced; subsequent cases still attempted (best-effort drain).
[Change] src/bl.d/90-main.sh — `bl flush --session-events [--case <id>]` route
      added. Without --case, flushes every open case from session_ids. Mirrors
      the existing `bl flush --outbox` operator entry point.
[Change] src/bl.d/30-preflight.sh — bl_help_flush rewritten with both targets.
[Change] schemas/step.json — `properties.custom_tool_use_id` (string, optional)
      added so bl_jq_schema_check --strict accepts bridge-enriched bodies.
      Pattern is documentary (jq-check honors required/enum/additionalProperties
      only — pattern is not enforced runtime). No per-field `description` —
      Anthropic agents API rejects that keyword inside input_schema.
[Change] schemas/step.md — full doc for custom_tool_use_id including the
      curator-vs-bridge authorship boundary.
[Change] src/bl.d/00-header.sh — BL_VERSION 0.5.2 → 0.6.0 (architecture
      addition: bridge becomes a first-class operator-invokable verb).
[New] tests/03-bridge.bats — 12 tests covering report_step extraction,
      custom_tool_use_id enrichment, cursor advance + reuse, idempotent
      re-post (409→success), non-report_step skip, no-session no-op,
      missing/malformed case-id, and bl flush --session-events dispatch.
[New] tests/fixtures/sessions-events-bridge-*.json — 2 mock session-event
      fixtures (3-report-steps + empty) for bridge BATS coverage.
[New] tests/fixtures/memstore-bridge-step-post-ok.json — mock memstore POST
      response shape.

=== M16 P2 — 2026-04-26 (cron --from-file fixture-mode adapter) ===

[New] src/bl.d/41-observe-collectors.sh — bl_observe_cron `--from-file <path>`
      reads a static crontab fixture (or LMD post-scan adapter snapshot) and
      emits cron.entry records the same way --user/--system already do. Mutex
      against --user/--system: combining live system state with a static
      snapshot would silently merge unrelated time-frames. Unreadable path
      returns 72; format is otherwise identical to live read.
[Change] tests/04-observe.bats — 5 new tests under Group: cron covering
      happy path emit, ANSI-obscured detection on fixture content, both mutex
      paths (user + system) returning 64, and unreadable path returning 72.

=== M16 P1 — 2026-04-26 (modsec collector parser + corpus alignment) ===

[Fix] src/bl.d/41-observe-collectors.sh — _parse_modsec_serial section
      tracking. Prior `/^[A-Z]$/` regex never matched (ModSec embeds the
      section letter in the boundary line, not on its own); section state
      stayed empty so total_records was always 0 against any corpus.
      Now extracts letter from the boundary via portable substr(), accepts
      both single-line canonical Section A (`[ts] uid client-ip ...`) and
      legacy 2-line form (uid + Apache time). JSON value escaping added —
      embedded quotes in rule_msgs would emit invalid JSON that broke jq
      downstream. 570 records now parse from fleet-01 large-corpus.
[Change] scripts/dev/synth-corpus.sh — modsec generator emits canonical
      8-hex transaction ids (per skills/linux-forensics/modsec-audit-format.md
      and Apache mod_unique_id convention) instead of multi-segment
      `txn-NNNNNN-XXXX`. Section A body uses Apache common-log time format
      with embedded uid + client/server tuples — the form `bl observe log
      modsec` actually parses.
[Change] exhibits/fleet-01/large-corpus/modsec_audit.log — regenerated from
      seed 42; 570 transactions × 9 lines = 5130 lines. sha256 drift expected.

